    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>When does ovulation occur in a typical menstrual cycle?</summary>
        <p>Ovulation typically occurs about 14 days before the start of your next period, not 14 days after the start of your last period. In a standard 28-day cycle, this means ovulation happens around day 14. However, in a 32-day cycle, ovulation would occur around day 18, and in a 26-day cycle around day 12. The luteal phase (the time between ovulation and your next period) is relatively consistent at 12 to 14 days, while the follicular phase (before ovulation) varies more between individuals.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How long is the fertile window?</summary>
        <p>The fertile window lasts approximately six days: the five days before ovulation plus the day of ovulation itself. Sperm can survive in the female reproductive tract for up to five days, while an egg is viable for only 12 to 24 hours after release. This means conception is possible from intercourse that occurs up to five days before ovulation through the day of ovulation. The two to three days immediately before ovulation are generally the most fertile, as sperm are already in position when the egg is released.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can you ovulate twice in one cycle?</summary>
        <p>It is possible to release two or more eggs during ovulation, but this happens within the same 24-hour window, not on separate days. This is called multiple ovulation and is how fraternal twins are conceived. Once ovulation occurs, rising progesterone levels prevent additional eggs from being released later in the same cycle. You cannot ovulate on day 14 and then ovulate again on day 20 of the same cycle. Fertility drugs like Clomid intentionally stimulate multiple ovulation to increase the chances of conception.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What are the physical signs of ovulation?</summary>
        <p>Common signs of ovulation include a change in cervical mucus to a clear, stretchy, egg-white consistency; a slight rise in basal body temperature of about 0.4 to 1.0 degrees Fahrenheit after ovulation; mild pelvic pain or cramping on one side called mittelschmerz; increased libido; breast tenderness; light spotting; and a positive ovulation predictor kit (OPK) test showing an LH surge. Not every person experiences all of these signs, and some may not notice any symptoms at all.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do you track ovulation with irregular cycles?</summary>
        <p>With irregular cycles, calendar-based predictions alone are unreliable. Instead, use physical tracking methods such as daily basal body temperature (BBT) charting to identify the post-ovulation temperature shift, monitoring cervical mucus changes for the egg-white consistency that signals approaching ovulation, and ovulation predictor kits (OPKs) that detect the LH surge 24 to 36 hours before ovulation. Combining all three methods provides the most accurate picture. If your cycles are consistently irregular (shorter than 21 days or longer than 35 days), consult a healthcare provider to rule out conditions like PCOS or thyroid disorders.</p>
      </details>
    </section>

